The electrochemical properties of H@TNAs-1 were evaluated firstly by cyclic voltammetry (CV), within a potential window of − 0.3~0.5 V (vs. SCE) at various scan rates from 10 to 500 mV s−1. As shown in Fig. 5a, the CV curves displayed ideal quasi-rectangular shapes even at the highest scan rate of 500 mV s−1, suggesting H@TNAs-1 exhibited an extraordinary capacitive property. The charge/discharge curves at various current densities were shown in Fig. 5b; the curves kept good linearity and symmetry regardless of the current density, indicating the excellent reversibility of charge/discharge process. The specific capacitance of H@TNAs-1 was calculated by Eq. (2) [54, 55]:2C=2im∫VdtV2vivf\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
